Well, then, the first thing to recommend to a young (1) by a military man in his quest for glory is that he try to win it, if career, he can, in a military career. Among our forefathers many distinguished themselves as soldiers3 for war- fare was almost continuous then. The period of your own youth, however, has coincided with that war in which the one side was too prolific in crime, the other in failure. And yet, when Pompey placed you in command of a cavalry squadron in this war, you won the applause of that great man and of the army for your skill in riding and spear-throwing and for endurance of all the hardships of the soldier's life.

But that credit accorded to you came to nothing along with the fall of the republic.

The subject of this discussion, however, is not your personal history, but the general theme. Let us, therefore, proceed to the sequel.
